<em><font size=-1>
<nobr>Mastering the lawless science of our law,--<br>
That <b>code</b>less myriad of precedent,<br>
That wilderness of single instances.<p>
-- Alfred Lord Tennyson
</nobr>
</font>
</em>
<p>
CODE is a visual parallel programming system, allowing users to compose sequential
programs into a parallel one. The parallel program is a directed graph, where
data flows on arcs connecting the nodes representing the sequential programs. The
sequential programs may be written in any language, and CODE will produce parallel
programs for a variety of architectures, as its model is architecture-independent.<p>

Click here for <a href="http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/code/code2.1b1-screenshot.gif">a screen shot</A>.<p>

<!--
To learn more about using CODE, read <A HREF="http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/code/CodeIntroduction.html">the tutorial</A> <IMG ALIGN=absmiddle SRC="http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/code/constru2.gif">.<p>
-->

The CODE system can produce parallel programs for <A HREF="http://www.epm.ornl.gov/pvm/pvm_home.html">PVM</A>-based networks of machines as well as for the <A HREF="http://www.sequent.com/">Sequent</A> Symmetry. The newest version (pre-release available below) supports the <A HREF="http://www.cray.com">Cray</A>, <A HREF="http://www.sun.com/">Sun</A> SMPs, and <A HREF="http://www.mcs.anl.gov/Projects/mpi/index.html">MPI</A>.
</dl>

</td></tr>
</table>

